Core Message

A denial is not the end ‚Äî it‚Äôs a pivot point. You can preserve, reframe, and escalate.

‚∏ª

Lesson Introduction

When the court denies relief, the worst mistake is treating it as final. Many rulings are procedural, partial, or made without prejudice. Each one can be leveraged into the next move.

‚∏ª

Teaching Block

1. Preserve the Issue
	‚Ä¢	File a Notice of Appeal or Motion for Reconsideration immediately if deadlines loom.

2. Change the Angle
	‚Ä¢	Shift to a different procedural vehicle (e.g., injunction ‚Üí declaratory judgment).

3. Stack the Record
	‚Ä¢	Ensure your appellate record shows the court had every chance to rule correctly.

‚∏ª

Real-World Illustration

After a TRO denial, re-filing as a preliminary injunction motion preserved federal review while an appeal was prepared.

‚∏ª

Assignment Prompt

Task:
List two follow-up moves after a denial of a discovery motion.

‚∏ª

Model Answer (Sample)
	1.	File a narrowed motion focusing on essential documents.
	2.	Seek interlocutory appeal if permitted.

‚∏ª

Reflection Summary

Denial is a door ‚Äî not a wall.

